# JAX + Equinox + Optax Stack

This project uses **JAX** (arrays & transforms), **Equinox** (modules), and **Optax** (optimizers). Do not introduce PyTorch, TensorFlow, or other frameworks.

## Modules

- Subclass `eqx.Module` for all learnable components.
- Annotate every field. Mark non-differentiable / non-array fields with `eqx.field(static=True)`.
- Accept `*, key: jax.Array` as a keyword argument in `__init__` when the initialisation uses randomness; omit or default to `None` when init is deterministic.
- Implement forward logic in `__call__`, not a separate `forward` method.

## Transforms & JIT

- Write pure functions — no in-place mutation, no Python-level side effects inside JIT-traced code.
- Use `eqx.filter_jit` instead of bare `jax.jit` to handle Equinox modules.
- Use `eqx.filter_grad` / `eqx.filter_value_and_grad` for gradient computation.
- Prefer `jax.vmap` over manual batch dimensions when the per-example logic is clearer unbatched.

## Training Loop

- Build optimizers with `optax` (e.g. `optax.adamw`).
- Carry optimizer state as a PyTree; update with `optax.apply_updates`.
- Use `eqx.apply_updates` to produce new model PyTrees — never mutate in place.

## Arrays

- Use `jax.numpy` (`jnp`) for all tensor operations.
- Avoid NumPy in any code path that will be JIT-compiled; use `np` only for data preprocessing outside JAX.
- Prefer `jnp.where` over Python `if/else` on traced values; use Python `if` only on static fields or shapes.
